INSERT INTO `field_revision_body` (`entity_type`, `bundle`, `deleted`, `entity_id`, `revision_id`, `language`, `delta`, `body_value`, `body_summary`, `body_format`) VALUES ('node','tip',0,2,2,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It is important to encourage students to learn from each bug or mistake instead of letting them get discouraged.</li>\r\n<li>This encouragement is especially necessary for girls because they\'re more likely to drop out of tech coursework because they\'re afraid they won\'t succeed as opposed to actually failing academic work.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,4,4,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Emphasize how careers in STEM fields can hugely impact society for more socially-minded students.</li>\r\n<li>There are projected to be 1.4 million job openings in computer science by 2020, and the number of women in the field is dropping. Without these women, we won’t be able to fill all these jobs!</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,5,5,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Showing students proof that others have succeeded in the industry helps them to believe they can succeed.</li>\r\n<li>Being exposed to a wide variety of careers in CS will help students find their niche and emphasize how applicable CS skills are to the elusive “real world.”</li>\r\n<li>Girls are often apprehensive of being the only girl in the room, but interacting with women mentors will make the tech industry seem like less of a “boys’ club.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,6,6,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This environment can be created by positive reinforcement and treating failures as learning experiences rather than a reason to give up.</li>\r\n<li>A positive environment encourages students to believe they can meet all the challenges they’ll face in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,7,7,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Women are huge consumers of technology, but they are underrepresented in its design.</li>\r\n<li>As a result, companies are seeking more diverse perspectives in design to become closer to their consumers and increase profits.</li>\r\n<li>Encourage productive collaboration by telling students that teams comprised of many gender identities are more creative and productive.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,8,8,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This is important encouragement for students who think computer science involves sitting alone at a computer all day.</li>\r\n<li>Provide opportunities to experience industry to allow students to see firsthand all the different tasks that occur in a computer science jobs.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,9,9,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This may encourage students to think carefully about their questions.</li>\r\n<li>It will also promote collaboration in a productive way as an important step in development.</li>\r\n</ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,10,10,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help teachers to design course curriculum based on the abilities of the students, and to highlight the subjects that might be most difficult for various students.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,11,11,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These basic, intro-level programming exercises will serve as introductions to the concepts of computer science, and can be telling for the ways students will struggle later on in terms of thinking about computer science concepts.</li>\r\n<li>More information about LightBot is available at: http://light-bot.com/</li>\r\n<li>More information about Picobot is available at: http://nifty.stanford.edu/2010/dodds-picobot/</li>\r\n<li>More information about Manufactoria is available at: http://pleasingfungus.com/Manufactoria/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,12,12,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will let students see the kind of opportunities they can have if they continue their studies in university.</li>\r\n<li>This can also connect interested students with potential mentors</li>\r\n<li>Students will also be able to see the older students as role models, which can be especially important for students who are minorities in the field.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,13,13,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Emphasizing the problem-solving nature of computer science can help students understand that programming, at its core, relies on learning computational thinking.</li>\r\n<li>By focusing on the cross-over skills one can gain in a computer science class, you\'ll encourage students who may not consider careers in computer science to take a computer science course.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,14,14,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This helps students to think about how they use programming tools in their daily lives, and makes lessons in the classroom seem more relevant to them.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,15,15,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be a fun exercise for more creative students, and it also requires an in-depth understanding of concepts.</li>\r\n<li> Below is an example poem from Hélène Martin. Check out her blog for more great poems!\r\n<code>\r\nMy mind has gone blank\r\nNow as void as a method\r\nthat does not return\r\n</code> </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,16,16,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This kind of content organization would allow students to logically build up knowledge.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,17,17,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A good way of doing this is to create a list of what you want your students to take away from the course and find an IDE that fits those goals.</li>\r\n<li>This will ensure that teaching isn’t hindered by issues with the development environment.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,18,18,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help build their confidence and show them various ways of problem solving the difficulties that come with writing code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,19,19,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This helps to keep the course focused, and prevents doing activities just because they’re “cool.”</li>\r\n<li>Clear goals will also help to keep all students on the same page with progression through the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,20,20,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will encourage incoming students, as they will have a greater connection to peers who have taken the course before.</li>\r\n<li>It will also give you the ability to see what struggles your students have had during the year and appreciate the various ways that they overcame these struggles.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,21,21,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A large variety of speakers can help students find their niche in the field as well as provide them with potential mentors for their future work in computer science.</li>\r\n<li>Guest speakers also show students that real people, not merely stereotypes, are involved in computer science!</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,24,24,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If an answer is incorrect, ask the student to explain why they think a certain approach is correct to determine where the misunderstanding lies.</li>\r\n<li>When explaining mistakes, focus specifically on the incorrect step a student takes instead of on the whole process. </li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>This will help your students feel more confident in their overall abilities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,25,25,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These generalizable skills help retain concepts with wide applications.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,26,26,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The most influential role models are those that students can easily believe in and relate to.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,27,27,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This also ensures a clear connection between what the students expect to learn and the course content.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,28,28,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The easiest resources to access independently are often quickly found through a search engine and are not password-protected.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,29,29,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students draft their own letters of recommendation in the beginning of the year using pre-written templates, e.g. “X created outstanding tests for his code, which I sometimes used to catch problems in other students’ code.” versus “X made clear that he considered testing a waste of time.” at the beginning of the year.</li>\r\n<li>Using this framework, students can reflect on what makes a positive letter of recommendation and, by extension, a good student.</li>\r\n<li>Remind students that they’re in charge of their own performance in class— letters of recommendation don’t just emerge from nowhere!</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,30,30,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Often, students will want to bypass proposals and design documents in favor of starting to code as quickly as possible.</li>\r\n<li>Focus on how much time can be saved by planning before coding.</li>\r\n<li>Remind students that if they review their ideas before implementing them, they can catch big issues and devise more efficient ways to write code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,31,31,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students make a lot of changes before testing, it is harder to keep track of what was changed. This can make debugging more time consuming and difficult, because they will often not know where their program is wrong or why their code isn\'t working.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,32,32,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students may find it funny or helpful to think about the “Five Stages of Code Review” (based on Dr. Elisabith Kubler-Ross’ book “Five Stages of Grief” from her book <em>On Death and Dying</em>):\r\n<ul><li>Disbelief: \"How could someone find so much to complain about in my code?!\"</li>\r\n<li>Anger: \"How dare someone suggest that a hash-map of hash-maps isn\'t an efficient way of storing data?\"</li>\r\n<li>Bargaining: \"Maybe if I add the comments the reviewer requested in one file, I won\'t have to fix the tricky Unicode issues in another.\"</li>\r\n<li>Depression: \"There was so much wrong with my code.  How can I show my face to the person who reviewed my code?\"</li>\r\n<li>Acceptance: \"Wow, my code is a lot better due to the feedback.  This is a useful process, although I bet it\'s occasionally painful for everyone.\"</li></ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,33,33,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Share relevant jokes, anecdotes, or webcomics— these are often written by and for programmers, and can remind students that even as a professional, things like being reviewed are still stressful; sometimes humorously so!</li>\r\n<li>Tell personal anecdotes about programming debacles. These remind students that they’re not alone.</li>\r\n</il>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,34,34,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Use students’ names in class, rather than labels like “the girl with the red hair.”</li>\r\n<li>This makes it easier to interact will all students, rather than only the ones whose names you know.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,35,35,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can prevent the creation of an informal student hierarchy that puts students with previous CS experience at the top.</li>\r\n<li>By not labeling experienced students as “smarter,” inexperienced students should feel more comfortable speaking up in class.</li>\r\n<li>To foster a more inclusive learning environment, remind that being \"smart\" is not limited to having programming experience, that there are many kinds of expertise. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,36,36,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This prevents students from feeling they’re not “smart” because they didn’t do well on a test other students thought was “a slam dunk.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,37,37,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Calling on all students equally will make everyone feel more comfortable asking and answering questions, even if they’re not completely confident with their answer.</li>\r\n<li>You can accomplish this by having a mechanism where you make sure all students get called on once before calling on any student a second time.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,38,38,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This shows students that the most important part of their education is learning the concepts and how to think about problems.</li>\r\n<li>If the logic of the code is correct, not penalizing small bugs in programs helps students realize mistakes are okay and they don’t have to be perfect.</li>\r\n<li>“A learning environment should be a place where making a mistake is an acceptable action.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,39,39,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Make sure not to favor students and ensure that students who don’t talk much are heard.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,41,41,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students are told that their solution is just as valid as a solution created by an instructor, they will be more confident in their abilities.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,42,42,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For example, some students may need to understand how they can apply their knowledge before they learn the details.</li>\r\n<li>Try different instruction methods to support these learning styles.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,44,44,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It is important that students have a chance to work with content before assigning homework that builds on that material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,45,45,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students often get stuck and cannot demonstrate understanding when trying to parse unfamiliar syntax.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,47,47,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When a course has clear prerequisites, you avoid devoting a lot of lecture time to teaching concepts students already know.</li>\r\n<li>It can be particularly difficult to match the pace of an intro course with the pace of the students when you have both students that are new to Computer Science and others that are already experienced.</li>\r\n<li>It can be helpful to split an intro course into two separate courses: one for students new to Computer Science and another for those that are experienced.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,48,48,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When certain assignments receive low scores across classes, it’s probably an indication that the assignment is ineffective.</li>\r\n<li>Incorporate a mechanism for identifying ineffective assignments to ensure meaningful coursework.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,49,49,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>A lack of comfort with environments such as Unix can obstruct students\' focus on the learning objective.</li>\r\n<li>Video tutorials that familiarize students with environments can be an essential resource. Post these on your class website or YouTube channel.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,50,50,'und',0,'<ul><li>Useful tools that may not be explicitly part of the curriculum include:\r\n<ul><li>debugging</li>\r\n<li>language-specific syntax (Unix in particular)</li>\r\n<li>breaking down a problem into bite-size pieces</li>\r\n<li>how to use a coding environment like Eclipse</li></ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,51,51,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Ask students what components need to go in each part of a ‘for loop’ first, to help support them in writing well-developed ‘for loops.’</li>\r\n<li>Encourage students to write helper functions as opposed to lengthy, multi-purpose functions by limiting the number of lines a function can be.</li>\r\n<li>Explain that the process of breaking a problem into pieces is also helpful for solving problems in industry.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,52,52,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Explicitly write, cross out, and update variable-value pairs when tracing through code that iterates.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,53,53,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>It can be helpful to draw an arrow from one diagram to the next to indicate where a function call was made and that control is being passed. After the call has completed, the arrow can be erased to indicate a return of control.</li>\r\n<li>This method can also be applied when teaching Assembly -- have the diagrams represent the different phases of the stack.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,54,54,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>More explicitly consider the following conversation metaphor: A primary function may ASK a secondary function a QUESTION by calling it. The secondary function RESPONDS by returning an answer.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,56,56,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If technical language is necessary, be sure to give sufficient definitions.</li>\r\n<li>Peer tutors can be helpful for reiterating information to students in a more colloquial manner, like reinforcing technical definitions.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,59,59,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students think about the goal at the highest level and work their way back to the code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,60,60,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Help students see writing code as a way to translate their ideas to the computer.</li>\r\n<li>Students often get stuck developing a solution in terms of the syntax of a specific programming language.</li>\r\n<li>Consider requiring that your students turn in a pseudocode solution to an assignment before allowing them to begin programming.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,61,61,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These interests might include designing and building games.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,62,62,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be used to help with teaching algorithms, data structures, and other more complex concepts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,63,63,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The extra motivation can push students to better learn covered material and learn more material in order to make their assignments fit their desired outcome.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,64,64,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This is an essential programming skill that they can apply to almost any problem they have to solve in CS.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,66,66,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Collaborate with coworkers to make use of everyone’s strengths.</li>\r\n<li>It is often helpful to see other teachers’ real lessons, from online video libraries or your colleagues’ lectures, to improve your own lesson planning.</li>\r\n<li>New pedagogical research can often be incorporated into your classroom technique.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,67,67,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This approach to course design incentivizes students to endure more difficult assignments on which they might otherwise give up.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,68,68,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Schedule time to meet with students and discuss their performance, their time management strategies, and how they can improve.</li>\r\n<li>Write personalized notes to each student. 2-3 sentences can go a long way.</li>\r\n<li>If you find the note creation process too time consuming, consider writing a script that personalizes notes or emails based on parameters such as scores and class participation.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,69,69,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Sharing your own struggles can also help you connect with your students.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,70,70,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Given the easy access to Computer Science resources outside of the classroom, students may feel intimidated by those that are already knowledgeable of course content.</li>\r\n<li>Tell students that learning is a process, and even though people may be at different stages in the process, everyone is going in the same direction.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,72,72,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If you have access to iClickers, consider polling your students during class to gauge how far into an assignment they are.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,73,73,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Tell students that reading an assignment and making mental or physical notes counts as starting it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,75,75,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Discuss what went wrong and how to improve.</li>\r\n<li>Encourage students to not be content until they fully understand a topic.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,76,76,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Encourage students to take pride in gaining new understanding.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,78,78,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Seeing peers teaching gives students confidence that they, too, can understand the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,80,80,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://www.problets.org/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,81,81,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://codingbat.com/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,82,82,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Find the resource at http://byob.berkeley.edu/</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,83,83,'und',0,'Find the resource at http://practiceit.cs.washington.edu/practiceit/','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,84,84,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For instance, assign students to roles where other students feel comfortable asking them for help, such as group leaders.</li>\r\n<li>This reiterates the confidence you have in your students.</li>\r\n<li>In addition, students may learn better from peers.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,85,85,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This also demonstrates to students that you are equally confident in all their abilities.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,86,86,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Common issues to look out for include attempts to assume leadership roles because, stereotypically, boys may be seen as more “appropriate” leaders than girls.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,87,87,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The goals of any task, as explained by the teacher, guide the student towards what is important.</li>\r\n<li>Without such guidance, it is easy for students to get confused about what the point of a particular exercise was.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,88,88,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>In particular, one-on-one conversations can encourage them to open up and share concerns.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,89,89,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students create clones with another block, like “when spacebar pressed”, these clones will also create clones when the spacebar is pressed, so the total number of clones increases by a factor of 2 every time the spacebar is pressed. This is generally unwanted behavior.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,90,90,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Create Your Own Block can be used to store useful things like helper functions. This can make it easier to teach students how to break up large problems in Scratch and can thus help with debugging. Students can easily test which of their smaller functions is not working properly.</li>\r\n<li>There are also many scripts that students will use often (like a script that clears the stage and moves the sprite to center) that can be made into a single procedure with Create Your Own Block. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,91,91,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>The \"<cite>top-down process</cite>\" involves \"dividing a large program into modular pieces with a clear logical structure,\"  essentially decomposing a problem.</li>\r\n<li>The \"<cite>bottom-up process</cite>\" is a \"way of building complex problems... [by] combining existing procedures,\" fundamentally composing a solution from already existing pieces.</li>\r\n<li>The \"\'build your own block\'\" feature in Scratch provides a way for students to define simple procedures and helper functions that can then be called to create more complex procedures. For example, students can make a block that draws a petal/leaf which they can then use this block as a sub-routine in a script that draws an entire flower.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,92,92,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Scope works a little differently in Scratch than in other languages. A variable that is “For this sprite only” can still be read by other sprites, but only the sprite that owns it can write to it. Variables that exist “For all sprites” act like global variables. This can help students when deciding what scope of variables to use for different tasks.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,93,93,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will show students that they can always learn something new, so they shouldn’t expect to learn everything now.</li>\r\n<li>This will also help students figure out good ways of learning new things by watching you learn.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,94,94,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help them feel less discouraged if they get stuck, or a problem takes them a long time to figure out.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,95,95,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If a strategy is successful for one student, it’s likely it can be successful for other students.</li>\r\n<li>Take the opportunity to learn from your students to improve how you teach the material.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,96,96,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help you keep track of how students are progressing, as well as see what concepts are more difficult and might require more time, and which are easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,97,97,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can be accomplished in a variety of ways, such as letting the student come up with the main idea, and then come up with an action plan for the project.</li>\r\n<li>This will help both of you expand your knowledge of the project.</li>\r\n<li>You can also use this as an opportunity to help students start the project, which can be one of the hardest parts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,98,98,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Questions can help you determine what students are struggling with and help you scaffold their learning in a better direction.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,99,99,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will allow your students to follow a similar procedure when they work alone on assignments.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,100,100,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students see exactly where their code is going wrong, so they know what part of their code needs to be fixed.</li>\r\n<li>This can also help students understand how their programs run, so in the future debugging will be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,101,101,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These should include interesting challenges you know at least one way to solve.</li>\r\n<li>You could also motivate your students to try to find other solutions to the challenges.</li>\r\n<li>For example, writing a procedure that draws your initials, or asks knock-knock jokes.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,102,102,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students think about the concepts in another way, which can help with their understanding.</li>\r\n<li>For example, have your students think about information stored on the disk as a notebook they keep adding information to.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,103,103,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students will realize that everyone gets bugs, even people with coding experience.</li>\r\n<li>Use this opportunity to emphasize that finding and getting rid of bugs is a learning experience, so next time it’ll be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,104,104,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>“If you can describe it, you can solve it!”</li>\r\n<li>If students can correctly describe their bugs, they know exactly what it’s doing. This enables them to figure out how to get rid of it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,105,105,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students compare what their code is doing and what the description explains it should be doing, they may be able to determine where their error is.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,106,106,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If the code is in smaller pieces, it’s easier to pinpoint what parts aren’t working and focus on them rather than the entire program.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,107,107,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can also help students determine what bugs they tend to make so they can avoid making the same bugs in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,108,108,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>“A rested, relaxed mind may just get the solution without trying!”</li>\r\n<li>Just like while sleeping, their brain will keep thinking about the problem during the break, so when they come back to working it will be easier.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,109,109,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Have students check the obvious and talk through the bug before getting involved.</li>\r\n<li>This will help students hone their debugging technique and help them debug on their own in the future.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,111,111,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Example topics and activities include:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>debugging</li>\r\n<li>analyzing raw code or output</li>\r\n<li>reflecting on intuition vs. reality</li>\r\n<li>writing a task using different methods</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,112,112,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Consider roles for:</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Keeping the group focused</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring everyone contributes and is heard</li>\r\n<li>Mediating between the group and those outside of it (including the teacher and the class)</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring that individual responses are consistent with group consensus</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring that the group’s work meets the expectations and is easy to understand</li>\r\n<li>Discussing with the group how the workflow could be improved</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,115,115,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can work well if students are creating games or websites.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,116,116,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Good examples can show students valuable ways to approach problems, and walk them through the steps.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,117,117,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This can help students with their problem-solving skills and determining how to write code that is compatible on many systems.</li>\r\n<li>Especially with HTML5, students can find pieces that aren’t compatible with all browsers.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,118,118,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>TED is a set of conferences with interesting and inspiring talks of varying length devoted to “ideas worth spreading.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,119,119,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students might not have enough time to finish an assignment because they get caught up in making a decision.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,122,122,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>See the table below for websites that have sample projects:\r\n<table border=\"1\" style=\"width:300px\">\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Programming Language</td><td>Sites</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Scratch</td><td>scratch.mit.edu</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</li></ul>','','full_html'),('node','tip',0,123,123,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Remind students that their programs could be used by people from different backgrounds, with different needs and experiences.</li>\r\n<li>Having a diverse team can help avoid oversights made when too many assumptions are made about one’s audience. For example, early car air bags were designed by a team of mostly male engineers who designed for and tested on only male bodies. Because of the oversight of women’s and children’s bodies in the design, many women and children died preventable deaths.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,124,124,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Be conscious that female students in computer science classes are sometimes “perpetually teased” (Margolis 35) by their male peers, and this can lead to a decrease in their interest in computer science, regardless of how much they enjoy the subject matter.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,125,125,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Refusing to tolerate this language will build a safer and more conscious classroom, where students and teachers are aware of how cultural expectations and assumptions play out in the classroom.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,126,126,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Female students and students of color are more likely to understate their level of interest or skill in computer science; be sure to consider this when hearing students talk about interest in computer science.</li>\r\n<li>“Researchers on gender and math and science have found that self-confidence, not ability, is the significant difference between male and female science students” (Margolis 81).</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,127,127,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Kingston, Ontario teacher Corina Koch found that when she let elementary-school students use the computers on a first-come, first-serve basis, boys “dominated” the computers and girls were pressured away from them. She combated this by assigning computer time and distributing it evenly, which gave all of her students a chance to use the computers. (Margolis 34)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,128,128,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>You risk losing students with examples they don’t understand. Write examples that need no background cultural knowledge.</li>\r\n<li>Note that, especially if you are a male teacher with mostly/all male students, “assignments and teaching examples often embed male-dominated interests and activities, such as sports statistics and card and number tricks.” Often, there’s “little in computer science instructional material” that intentionally attracts students with other interests. (Margolis 37).</li>\r\n<li>An example from csteachingtips.com: The city of Computopia sells green boxes for 5 gold pieces and red boxes for 4....</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,129,129,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Computer science skills extend well beyond careers in computing, as they require “higher-order critical thinking skills and problem-solving skills” that can benefit all students. (37)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,130,130,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Often, computer science textbooks primarily focus on the “technical detail” of computer science, rather than the ways in which “computing is integrally linked to critical investigations in medicine, environmental science, famine control, art, and music” (37).</li>\r\n<li>If you defer the interdisciplinary or real-world applications of computer science, you can give introductory students the false impression that computer science is just a lot of programming, “removed from real-world context and concerns”. (Margolis 56)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,131,131,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>In showing the diverse set of people working in computer science, and building on the enjoyment they take in their careers, you’re helping a wider range of students see themselves enjoying careers involving CS.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,132,132,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When you hear students explain what they like about programming, you create an opportunity to discover more CS topics and applications that interest them, thus engaging \"a wider range of students\" (59). </li>\r\n<li>In generating student feedback, you may discover they have “a more expansive set of metaphors” to describe the material than you had already come across. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,133,133,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>In <cite>Unlocking the Clubhouse</cite>, a high school computer science teacher argues that “staying up all night doing something is a sign of single-mindedness and possibly immaturity as well as love for the subject.” She goes on to emphasize: “If you are looking for this type of obsessive behavior, then you are looking for a typically young, male behavior. While some girls will exhibit it, most won’t. But it doesn’t mean they don’t love computer science!”. </li>\r\n<li>Men are often viewed as being hyper-focused on their computers, where women have more varied interests. However, a teacher notes that “it is important to note that it is not only women who resist a myopic focus on computers. Some men resist a narrow orientation but do not question their ability because their gender has not rendered them suspect.” (75)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,135,135,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students may be able to repeat given explanations of concepts without fundamentally understanding them. For example, a student may be able to say that a variable is like a box, but may still not be able to use variables successfully. </li>\r\n<li>Walk-throughs are very helpful for checking how well students understand state. Students should be able to articulate the state of variables/objects (i.e., the values of variables or private data members/object attributes) as they move through the code. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,136,136,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For motivating passing in values: if students have a helper function that draws a square and they are then asked to use the helper function in a function that draws squares all over the screen, it is easier to motivate passing in a location, because it needs to know where to draw a square.\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,137,137,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Many people think of conditional statements in terms of “until”--”until school ends”--rather than in terms of while--“while school is in session.” Thus, it’s helpful to think about how “doing something until” relates to while loops when writing conditions. “While (this) is true” is the same as “Until (this) is false.” This can help students reason more intuitively about while loops. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,138,138,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Giving students prompts that tell them exactly what to build may prove boring and unmotivating for them. Having prompts like “Make a game using at least (this many) instances of (this object, etc)” and giving them tools to make it allows room for students to build projects that they find interesting. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,139,139,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>These reminders enable young women to visualize themselves in CS careers.</li>\r\n<li>One of the most important factors influencing the pursuit of a CS degree is a young woman’s perception of CS and it’s associated careers.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,140,140,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Encouragement is one of the most influencing factors in a young woman’s decision to pursue Computer Science.</li>\r\n<li>“What matters most is encouragement, not whether this encouragement was from someone with technical experience.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,141,141,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students interested in puzzles, problem solving, and tinkering will ultimately be more likely to pursue CS.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,142,142,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Remember, students are rarely total newcomers to the world of computers. They often “come to school with a wealth of ‘informal’ knowledge” about how computers work, based on their interactions with video games, the internet, etc. While students are new to the world of formal computer science, don’t discount the existing familiarity many students have entering the classroom. (Kolikant 544)</li>\r\n<li>Students will naturally want to use their background knowledge of computers and apply this knowledge to new situations, even if it’s not applicable or misleading. To students, it’s likely completely logical to “use pieces of knowledge that were productive in previous situations even though they may no longer be so.” (Kolikant 544)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,143,143,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Some teachers have found it more effective to express the fundamentals of computer science “in a context that aligns with student interests”. Try to use students’ existing interests such that “core CS knowledge is taught ‘as answers to questions that the students naturally develop when working with the media program’ (Guzdial 2003, p. 105).” (Kolikant 547)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,144,144,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Young students can have a tendency to not check whether their output is correct or not, but are simply content with the program producing an output. They can also have a tendency to avoid edge cases; place additional focus on thorough program testing.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,145,145,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>For instance, when encountering an error from the user\'s perspective, the error may be tolerated if it does not “prevent achieving the... goal”. However, when encountering an error from a programmers perspective, a programmer’s prerogative is to solve the problem(e.g., an error message may simply be closed and ignored by a user, but should be an alarming sign of a problem for a programmer). </li>\r\n<li>In this context, students must be taught to approach the errors (and computers at large) as a programmer rather than a user.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,146,146,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Beginning students\' previous problem solving interactions with a computer are typically exclusively with the interface, such as “refreshing the browser or restarting the computer.”  </li>\r\n<li>When students don\'t break past the habit of relying on an interface, “the underlying layers [of a computer] remain opaque and are not used in problem-solving.” (Kolikant 546)</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,147,147,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Tools like Scratch, the programming language, can help students get acclimated to coding environments. </li>\r\n<li>This is in stark contrast to the syntax of professional programming languages, which may be overwhelming.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,148,148,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Yifat Ben-David Kolikant describes one teacher who explains her method: “I don’t attempt to make my students professional swimmers right from the start… We gradually transform to a state I would call ‘‘hybrid’’…until I announce that from now on I will no longer accept undocumented work.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,149,149,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>When students perceive themselves as “computer veterans,” they’re less likely to follow explicit instructions on design and analysis.</li>\r\n<li>In one study, students with strong backgrounds in computer science, taking an advanced course, often “delegitimized class assignments” because they felt they had enough background in computer science to determine the worthwhileness of their teacher’s assignments. Students in this class felt assignments were “unrepresentative of the computer world” and “In some cases, despite being aware that a speciﬁc program [of theirs] does not fully meet the requirements (i.e. the professional standards), students decided that it was good enough because ‘a user can’t tell.’”  Further, these students “attributed the teachers’ judgment that the program was incorrect to ‘pettiness’ (Ben-David Kolikant and Ben Ari 2008).</li>\r\n<li>As a teacher, take into account that many students are very involved in a “computer-oriented culture” and many consider themselves well-versed in the computing world, even though they’re usually newcomers to the world of programming.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,150,150,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Young students often consider a function <strong>working</strong> if it produces output. As a result, they may neglect to consider whether it produces the intended output.</li>\r\n<li>Yifat Ben-David Kolikant describes one teacher who cleverly combats this tendency: She “chose problems that would lead to clearly wrong onscreen feedback if incorrectly solved... One successful example was asking her students to use their own family details as test data for a program about familial relations, instead of using a hypothetical family. In this way, [the teacher] explained, unexpected output is noticed quickly by the students, motivating them to go back to their program code and reﬁne it.”</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,151,151,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n\r\n<li>This idea is built around Wiggins\' and McTighe\'s <cite>Understanding by Design</cite> methodology where \"each big idea is introduced with an essential question.\" \r\n<li>In this paper, Touretzky\'s outlines seven big ideas and corresponding questions for teaching a one semester upper level computer science course in robotics. One such example is as follows:  \"Big idea: Robots use sophisticated but imperfect <strong> computer vision algorithms</strong> to deduce real world object representations from arrays of pixels,\" Essential Question:\"\'How do robots see the world?\'\"</li>\r\n<li>Such discussions should expose students to advanced computer science concepts and encourage them to want to learn more.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,152,152,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students will be able to visualize interesting things they can accomplish by the end of the course.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,153,153,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students understand what they and their technologies are doing.</li>\r\n<li>For example, when teaching robotics, \"describe particle filters and how they’re used by the Pilot for localization.\"</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,154,154,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>“Seeing” algorithms helps students understand how they work.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,155,155,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Exploring the technology they are expected to use in the course will also help students learn more about it and be able to use it better.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,156,156,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students review their knowledge, and help you determine how students are doing.</li>\r\n<li>You can use the information you gather from students to adjust how and what you’re teaching.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,157,157,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students may believe that variables can store unresolved mathematical expressions. </li>\r\n<li>When we have the assignment <code>var1 = var2 + var3</code>, they assume that a change to <code>var2</code> or <code>var3</code> after this assignment will change <code>var1</code> change without explicitly reassigning <code>var1</code>. </li>\r\n<li>This is because they think <code>var1</code> holds the expression <code>var2+var3</code> not the value of the result.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,158,158,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>E.g., \r\n<code>count1 = 3;\r\ncount2 = 2;\r\nsum = count2 + count1;\r\ncount1 = 4; </code>\r\nIn this example, the value of <code>sum</code> is 5 because the variable <code>sum</code> has not been redefined or reassigned. The variable <code>sum</code> will retain its value of 5 until it is assigned another value. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,159,159,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>4 = x and x = 4 are both valid mathematical expressions; however, variable assignment is only of the form <code>variable = value/object</code>.</li>\r\n<li>Because x and y (as well as z, a, b, and c) are common variable names in math problems and they are joined to a value by a sign (=) used in both math and computer science, students may be misled into believing that variable assignment and mathematical expressions have the same properties and are interchangeable. </li>\r\n<li>Suggest variable names that describe properties of the variable, such as what information it contains or what it will be used for. </li>\r\n <li>Using descriptive variable names may prove useful in helping students understand the differences between variable assignment and math expressions and may encourage the common practice of using descriptive variable names that make debugging easier. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,160,160,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students have the misconception that returning values or objects is the same as storing them. </li>\r\n<li>Students may also believe that simply typing the value or calling the constructor without assigning it to a variable “saves” the value or object for later use. </li>\r\n<li>These values and objects cease to exist once they are returned or created without being assigning to a variable.</li>\r\n<li>Therefore, it’s important to remind students that values and objects that are returned but not assigned to variables, or are created without assignment, are conceptually in limbo where they cannot ever be used again. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,161,161,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students have trouble understanding and describing the state of an object, i.e., the values of its attributes/private data members.</li>\r\n<li>They also have trouble describing the state of an object or variable within methods, which may impede them from writing successful methods. </li>\r\n<li>Students sometimes believe that two objects of the same class with the same attribute values are the same object.</li>\r\n<li>Students may also have the misconception that two objects of the same class can’t have the same attribute values.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,162,162,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Students have the misconception that objects “know” what methods are operating on them, rather than methods “knowing” what objects they are operating on. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,163,163,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n\r\n<li>In this activity, the instructor brings the supplies necessary to make a peanut butter and jelly sandwich. Next, the teacher directs students to individually write a list of instructions that the student will use to guide the teacher in making a PB&J sandwich.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>This activity, from an article by Janet Davis and Samuel A. Rebelsky, helps students understand that, in order to develop a successful algorithm, they have to:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>know what data is available,</li>\r\n<li>know what basic functions/methods/operations are available,</li>\r\n<li>be able to handle special cases,</li>\r\n<li>sequence operations properly,</li>\r\n<li>and understand the level of detail required.</li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n\r\n<li>This activity underscores how easily instructions can be misinterpreted, even if students think the steps are clear.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Students assume that computers interpret their instructions within a logical framework akin to their own, leading to flawed reasoning about what needs to be specified within algorithms.</li>\r\n<li>Tell students that \"Computers are sentient and malicious\": they will purposefully misinterpret instructions wherever possible. Suggest that students write code with the mindset that their instructions will be misinterpreted.</li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n\r\n<li>This activity can emphasize the benefits of collaboration.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have students work on creating instructions in groups after completing the task alone.</li>\r\n<li>This allows students to see how having other students’ input can help them identify problems in their proposed solutions, leading to better algorithms.</li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n\r\n<li>To make the activity more challenging:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Use jars of jelly that have a pry top, rather than a screw top, to teach students that it’s necessary to consider special cases.</li>\r\n<li>You can also include jars that have seals and bags of bread closed with twist-ties. </li>\r\n<li>If knives are used, carefullly grab by the blade instead of the handle, unless students instruct otherwise. </li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n\r\n<li>Remember that the activity should not be so frustrating that students don’t make progress and don’t enjoy it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,165,165,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li> When you give students code, ask questions about the following topics: what they think the code will do, what the values and states of variables are at various places in the code, and what the states of the objects are at various places in the code.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,166,166,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Some instructional resources provide videos for teachers to use in class; however, these videos may be too long to keep students engaged. </li>\r\n<li>If these videos are watched as a class, and not individually, pause the video every once in a while to ask students questions about the content. </li>\r\n<li>Reflecting on what they’ve seen may help them better absorb the content. </li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,167,167,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Beginner students often assume you must put a semicolon at the end of each line.</li>\r\n<li>Some other languages that include similar syntax are C, C++ and PHP.\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,168,168,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>If students cannot parse the code properly, they will not be able to understand what it is doing.</li>\r\n<li>This is especially important for beginning students who miss fundamental concepts when trying to write elegant code without understanding the thinking behind it.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,169,169,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>Teaching students without using shortcuts will help them to gain foundational knowledge, as well as build up their intuition for complicated concepts.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html'),('node','tip',0,170,170,'und',0,'<ul>\r\n<li>This will help students to understand the basics of each loop and conditional statement.</li>\r\n<li>It will also help students avoid unnecessary refactoring of code later on.</li>\r\n</ul>','','filtered_html');
