es in Scratch to avoid exponential cloning.',1,1,1405543714,1407183245,1,1,0,0,0),(90,90,'tip','und','Encourage students to use Create Your Own Block to store procedures in Scratch to help ease debugging.',1,1,1405543803,1407177541,1,1,0,0,0),(91,91,'tip','und','Use the \"\'build your own block\'\" feature in Scratch 2.0 to teach \"bottom-up\" or \"top-down\" processes for breaking up problems.',1,1,1405543973,1407177189,1,1,0,0,0),(92,92,'tip','und','Teach the concept of a variable’s scope in Scratch by explaining the difference between “For this sprite only” and “For all sprites.”',1,1,1405544100,1407177565,1,1,0,0,0),(93,93,'tip','und','If you discover something new in class, use the opportunity to show your students that learning opportunities are always present.',1,1,1405544797,1407177692,1,1,0,0,0),(94,94,'tip','und','Remind students that many problems take time and thought to solve.',1,1,1405544934,1407174590,1,1,0,0,0),(95,95,'tip','und','Make note of how students solve their own problems to identify successful problem-solving strategies.',1,1,1405545399,1407183276,1,1,0,0,0),(96,96,'tip','und','Keep records of students’ work to be able to modify things that prove less successful.',1,1,1405546201,1407191993,1,1,0,0,0),(97,97,'tip','und','Start the process of creating a project together with the student.',1,1,1405546332,1407177720,1,1,0,0,0),(98,98,'tip','und','Ask questions as an opportunity to help and learn from your students.',1,1,1405549041,1407184996,1,1,0,0,0),(99,99,'tip','und','Talk through your code as you write it so students learn how to approach problems.',1,1,1405549150,1407174566,1,1,0,0,0),(100,100,'tip','und','Help students find bugs by drawing or writing out what their code does at each step.',1,1,1405549258,1407202779,1,1,0,0,0),(101,101,'tip','und','Keep a bag of “survival tricks” on hand that will keep students interested and motivated.',1,1,1405549380,1407187923,1,1,0,0,0),(102,102,'tip','und','Use metaphors to describe how concepts work