d to start and complete it.','',1405554005,1,1,1,0),(121,121,1,'Be aware of students’ math background so you can prepare material to scaffold students for course content.','',1405554059,1,1,1,0),(122,122,1,'Prepare example projects and code to inspire students and clarify expectations.','',1405554333,1,1,1,0),(123,123,1,'Have students clearly outline who their audience is when designing a project so they can tailor to the users’ needs.','',1407178253,1,1,1,0),(124,124,1,'To ensure equitable access in your classroom, don’t allow language reinforcing the idea that computer science is “guy stuff” in the classroom, even passively.','',1407182620,1,1,1,0),(125,125,1,'Speak to students directly if they use language that downplays the ability of women and students of color.','',1407182835,1,1,1,0),(126,126,1,'Take the time to encourage girls and students of color as they often internalize cultural expectations that they have little innate CS ability.','',1407178492,1,1,1,0),(127,127,1,'Allocate computer time evenly among students, especially in elementary school, so all students get a chance to play.','',1407194921,1,1,1,0),(128,128,1,'Write made-up examples to avoid unknowingly introducing culturally-biased problems.','',1407173858,1,1,1,0),(129,129,1,'Ensure that students and counselors understand how CS is more than simply “a vocational skill” by highlighting how CS helps make critical thinkers and problem-solvers, too.','',1407182592,1,1,1,0),(130,130,1,'To engage a wider range of students in intro courses, be sure to highlight on the real-world context and applications of CS.','',1407182773,1,1,1,0),(131,131,1,'Show students the diverse set of people who hold CS careers. Make sure it’s clear that there is no one person, or one personality that exemplifies the field.','',1407203377,1,1,1,0),(132,132,1,'Ask students what they like about programming—it lets you know what to focus on so that students remain interested.','',1407177055,1,1,1,0),(133,133,1,'Don’t conflate interest in computer science with excessive amounts of time spent coding. This can discourage students who feel like they’re not into computer science because they don’t obsess over it.','',1407173645,1,1,1,0),(134,134,1,'Having high expectations, while important, is not sufficient for students’ success in CS.','',1405556148,1,1,1,0),(135,135,1,'Have students walk through and explain code to check for understanding.','',1405556232,1,1,1,0),(136,136,1,'Find examples that help motivate difficult abstract concepts, like passing in a value to a function.','',1405556315,1,1,1,0),(137,137,1,'To help students understand how a while loop executes, teach them that it runs “until” a condition is satisfied.','',1405556393,1,1,1,0),(138,138,1,'Provide open-ended prompts for building projects to keep students motivated. ','',1405556465,1,1,1,0),(139,139,1,'Remind girls that women in CS can have positive social impact to interest them in tech careers.','',1407182556,1,1,1,0),(140,140,1,'Have parents and peers also encourage students’ interest in Computer Science and problem solving to help influence their pursuit of it.','',1407182516,1,1,1,0),(141,141,1,'Use puzzles, etc. in assignments and activities to build students’ confidence and interest in pursuing Computer Science.','',1407182366,1,1,1,0),(142,142,1,'Students tend to make assumptions about computer science based on the experiences they’ve already had with computers.','',1407182323,1,1,1,0),(143,143,1,'When designing CS courses for total novices, write some assignments that allow students to make familiar or interesting things, e.g. making games or animations.','',1407178081,1,1,1,0),(144,144,1,'Ensure young CS students check their functions with a variety of inputs, as well as with edge cases.','',1407200091,1,1,1,0),(145,145,1,'Beginning students are used to viewing computers from a user’s perspective, and they subsequently have habits that may conflict with using the computer as a programmer.','',1407177232,1,1,1,0),(146